Interface List<E>

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    MedListArrayBased, MedListRefBased

    public interface List<E>
    A completed interface for a list container. This ADT specification is similar, but not identical to the List ADT described in the textbook.

    • Method Detail

      • add

        void add(E item,
         int index)
        Inserts an item to into the list at postion index. All items after the new item will have their index position increased by one. For example, if list is a list of integers {1,2,3}, then list.add(9,0) will alter the list to contain {9,1,2,3} in that order.
        Parameters:
        item - The object to add to the front of the list.
        index - The index position for the new item. Note that the index position may be equal to the number of items, meaning that the item will be placed at the end of the list.
        Throws:
        ListIndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is outside(0 … size).

      • remove

        void remove(int index)
        Removes the item at the index position of the list.
        Parameters:
        index - The index number.
        Throws:
        ListIndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is outside (0 … size-1).

      • get

        E get(int index)
        Accesses the item by its position in the list.
        Parameters:
        index - The index of the position.
        Returns:
        The item at that index position.
        Throws:
        ListIndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is outside (0 … size-1).

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Returns:
        true if the list is empty, false otherwise.

      • size

        int size()
        Returns:
        The number of items in the list.

      • find

        int find(E item)
        Determines if the equivalent item is in the list. If it is in the list, then the index location is returned. If it is not, then -1 is returned.
        Parameters:
        item - The item that is equivalent to the item we are looking for.
        Returns:
        The index position of the equivalent item or -1 if it is not in the list.

      • removeAll

        void removeAll()
        Removes all the items from the list, resulting in an empty list.

      • remove

        void remove(E value)
        Removes all matching items from the list. For example, if the list is made up of integers and contains {67,12,13,12}, then remove(12) will alter the list to {67,13}.
        Parameters:
        value - The item that identies what to remove. Any item in the list that matches this item will be removed. Note that if no matching item can be found, then nothing is removed.

      • toString

        java.lang.String toString()
        A printout of the list is in the form: List: {<item1>, <item2>, …, <last item>} where each item is the string returned by its toString method. Note that all the items can be listed on one line or placed on separate lines, depending on the aesthetics. An empty list is represented by List: {}
        Overrides:
        toString in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        The string representation of the list, formatted as above.
